# Regex for URLs in Markdown (Outside Code)

## The Honest Answer: Pure Regex Cannot Fully Solve This

**This is a context-sensitive parsing problem that regex alone cannot handle properly.** Here's why:

```
Markdown with code:
Check out https://example.com!      ✓ Should match
`https://example.com`               ✗ Should NOT match
```

Regex is fundamentally limited because it:
- Cannot track nested or balanced delimiters (backticks, triple-backticks)
- Cannot maintain state about whether you're "inside" or "outside" a code block
- Cannot handle different code block syntaxes (`` ` ``, ``` ``` ```, indentation)

## Best Practical Regex Approach

If you **must** use regex (e.g., in sed, grep, VS Code), here's a reasonable approximation:

```regex
(?<!`)(?<!``)https?://[^\s`<>\)]+(?!`)(?!``)
```

**Breakdown:**
- `(?<!`)` - Negative lookbehind: not preceded by backtick
- `(?<!``)` - Not preceded by double backtick (inline code delimiter)
- `https?://` - Match http or https
- `[^\s`<>\)]+` - One or more non-whitespace, non-backtick, non-angle-bracket chars
- `(?!`)` - Not followed by backtick
- `(?!``)` - Not followed by double backtick

**Test cases:**
```javascript
const regex = /(?<!`)(?<!``)https?:\/\/[^\s`<>)]+(?!`)(?!``)/g;

// ✓ Matches
"Check out https://example.com!".match(regex);  
// ["https://example.com"]

"Visit https://example.com and https://test.org".match(regex);
// ["https://example.com", "https://test.org"]

// ✗ Won't match (or partial failures)
"`https://example.com`".match(regex);  
// null (good!)

"```\nhttps://example.com\n```".match(regex);  
// ["https://example.com"] (BAD - still matches!)

"`code: https://example.com`".match(regex);
// null (good!)
```

## Better: Language-Specific Parser

Use a proper Markdown parser for reliable results:

### JavaScript/Node.js
```javascript
const markdownIt = require('markdown-it');
const md = new markdownIt();

function extractUrlsOutsideCode(markdown) {
  const tokens = md.parse(markdown, {});
  const urls = [];

  tokens.forEach(token => {
    // Only process text tokens, skip code blocks
    if (token.type === 'inline' && !token.block) {
      const urlRegex = /https?:\/\/[^\s<>)]+/g;
      let match;
      while ((match = urlRegex.exec(token.content)) !== null) {
        urls.push(match[0]);
      }
    }
  });

  return urls;
}

// Usage
const md = `
Check out https://example.com!

\`\`\`
wget https://example.com
\`\`\`

Inline code: \`https://example.com\` doesn't count.
`;

console.log(extractUrlsOutsideCode(md));
// ["https://example.com"]
```

### Python
```python
import re
import markdown
from markdown.treeprocessors import Treeprocessor

class URLExtractor(Treeprocessor):
    def run(self, root):
        self.urls = []
        self.extract_urls(root)
        return root

    def extract_urls(self, element):
        # Extract from text, skip code elements
        if element.tag not in ['code', 'pre']:
            if element.text:
                urls = re.findall(r'https?://[^\s<>)]+', element.text)
                self.urls.extend(urls)
            if element.tail:
                urls = re.findall(r'https?://[^\s<>)]+', element.tail)
                self.urls.extend(urls)

        for child in element:
            self.extract_urls(child)

md = markdown.Markdown()
extractor = URLExtractor(md.parser)
md.treeprocessors.register(extractor, 'url_extractor', 0)
```

## Summary Table

| Approach | Backtick Code | Fenced Code | Indented Code | Speed | Accuracy |
|----------|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Regex only** | ⚠️ Partial | ❌ No | ❌ No | ⚡ Fast | 40% |
| **Regex + context** | ✓ Yes | ⚠️ Partial | ❌ No | ⚡ Fast | 60% |
| **Markdown parser** | ✓ Yes | ✓ Yes | ✓ Yes | 🐢 Slower | 99% |

**Recommendation:** Use a parser. Regex is a tempting shortcut that will fail on real-world Markdown.
